???
- Thanks, xxx. Glad to be here.
- I'm going to be talking about the oversight and reform of police agencies
- and the statistical challenges posed by police records, which are a extremely
  problematic data source that show us only a fragment of all the information
  we'd like to see
- I'll show that we can still use this data to draw defensible conclusions about
 important social-scientific questions, if we're careful to think not just about
 what they show, but about all the thinks they *don't* show all the stuff that's
 distorted or omitted
- and to do this, I'll provide some computational algorithms that can help us
  with this reasoning
- by letting us do partial identification with incomplete data

---

# Police oversight: a review

--
- Among the most ubiquitous public organizations
  - Over 18k local law-enforcement agencies across US
  - Police contact >20% of Americans each year .tiny[(BJS, '22)]

--
- Vast discretion in enforcement of law .tiny[(Wilson '68, Goldstein, '77)]
  - "Street level bureaucrats" making real-time policy .tiny[(Lipsky '80)]

--
  - Elected principals cannot directly observe behavior of agents,
    hard to tell if civil-rights/public-safety interests are advanced

---

class: newspaper
<img src="./resources/images/headlines/nyt_doj_memphis_alpha.png" style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 15%; width: 80%; z-index: ;"/>

---

# Police oversight: a review

- Among the most ubiquitous public organizations
  - Over 18k local law-enforcement agencies across US
  - Police contact >20% of Americans each year .tiny[(BJS, '22)]
- Vast discretion in enforcement of law .tiny[(Wilson '68, Goldstein, '77)]
  - "Street level bureaucrats" making real-time policy .tiny[(Lipsky '80)]
  - Elected principals cannot directly observe behavior of agents,
    hard to tell if civil-rights/public-safety interests are advanced
- Main alignment mech. is "investigate and sanction"
  - Involves labor-intensive, deep-dive review of agency practices

--
  - But DOJ can examine only a handful of agencies at best
  - Litigation by NGOs is costly, can take years to go to trial

---

# Monitoring with open data

- Police data increasingly available .tiny[(Vera Institute, '23)]
- "Benchmark analysis" offers avenue for monitoring
  - **Retrospective:** assess if past policy reforms worked
  - **Prospective:** reduce principal-agent info. gap, <br>allow reward/punishment of alignment/deviation
- But lack of causal foundation &rightarrow; statistical challenges  &rightarrow; wildly contradictory findings .tiny[(Ridgeway '11)]

