<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 25%; line-height: 1.5">2.</h1>
<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 20%; top: 25%; line-height: 1.5">
  Implicit assumptions<br>
  in the current practice<br>
  of benchmark analysis
</h1>

---

# The standard estimator

- When does the odds ratio recover a causal risk ratio?
$$\small \frac{\text{# minority stops}}{\text{# white stops}} \Bigg/ \frac{\text{# minority in benchmark}}{\text{# white in benchmark}}$$

---

# The standard estimator

- When does the odds ratio recover a causal risk ratio?
$$\small \frac{\Pr(r_1 | s_1)}{\Pr(r_0 | s_1)} \Bigg/ \frac{\Pr(r_1 | c_1)}{\Pr(r_0 | c_1)}$$


---

<br><br>
<div class="box">
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 150%;"><b>Assumption 1.</b> ("Police don't lie.")</p>
<p>Police precision, $\mathrm{Pr}(d_1 | s_1)$, equals one.</p>
</div>

---

<br><br>
<div class="box">
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 150%;"><b>Assumption 1.</b> ("Police don't lie.")</p>
<p>Police precision, $\mathrm{Pr}(d_1 | s_1)$, equals one.</p>
</div>
<br><br><br><br>
<div class="box">
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 150%;"><b>Assumption 2.</b> ("Cameras don't lie.")</p>
<p>Proxy precision, $\mathrm{Pr}(d_1 | c_1)$, equals one.</p>
</div>

---

# The standard estimator

- When does the odds ratio recover a causal risk ratio?
  - Within $x$, under **Asms. 1–2** (officers & cameras don't lie)

--

$$\begin{aligned}
\small OR^x 
&= \frac{
	    \Pr(r_1 | s_1, x)
	}{
		\Pr(r_0 | s_1, x)
	} \Bigg/ \frac{
		\Pr(r_1 | c_1, x)
	}{
		\Pr(r_0 | c_1, x)
	} \\\\[2ex]
&\ {\color{white}=} \ \color{white}\frac{
	    \mathbb{E}\big[ \ \mathbf{1}(R=r_1) S \mid d_1, x \ \big] \big/ \Pr(r_1 | d_1, x)
	}{
		\mathbb{E}\big[ \ \mathbf{1}(R=r_0) S \mid d_1, x \ \big] \big/ \Pr(r_0 | d_1, x)
	} \\\\[2ex]
&\color{white}=	\color{white} RR^{d_1,x}
\end{aligned}$$

---

# The standard estimator

- When does the odds ratio recover a causal risk ratio?
  - Within $x$, under **Asms. 1–2** (officers & cameras don't lie)

$$\begin{aligned}
\small OR^x 
&\ {\color{black}=} \ \color{black}\frac{
	    \Pr(r_1 | s_1, d_1, x)
	}{
		\Pr(r_0 | s_1, d_1, x)
	} \Bigg/ \frac{
		\Pr(r_1 | {\color{#A51C30}c_1}, d_1, x)
	}{
		\Pr(r_0 | {\color{#A51C30}c_1}, d_1, x)
	} \\\\[2ex]
&\ {\color{white}=} \ \color{white}\frac{
	    \mathbb{E}\big[ \ \mathbf{1}(R=r_1) S \mid d_1, x \ \big] \big/ \Pr(r_1 | d_1, x)
	}{
		\mathbb{E}\big[ \ \mathbf{1}(R=r_0) S \mid d_1, x \ \big] \big/ \Pr(r_0 | d_1, x)
	} \\\\[2ex]
&\color{white}=	\color{white} RR^{d_1,x}
\end{aligned}$$

