# The standard estimator

- When does the odds ratio recover a causal risk ratio?
  - Within $x$, under **Asms. 1–2** (officers & cameras don't lie)

$$\begin{aligned}
\small OR^x 
&\ {\color{black}=} \ \color{black}\frac{
	    \Pr(r_1 | s_1, d_1, x)
	}{
		\Pr(r_0 | s_1, d_1, x)
	} \Bigg/ \frac{
		\Pr(r_1 | d_1, x)
	}{
		\Pr(r_0 | d_1, x)
	} \\\\[2ex]
&\ {\color{black}=} \ \color{black}\frac{
	    \mathbb{E}\big[ \ \mathbf{1}(R=r_1) S \mid d_1, x \ \big] \big/ \Pr(r_1 | d_1, x)
	}{
		\mathbb{E}\big[ \ \mathbf{1}(R=r_0) S \mid d_1, x \ \big] \big/ \Pr(r_0 | d_1, x)
	} \\\\[2ex]
&\color{black}=	\color{black} RR^{d_1,x}
\end{aligned}$$

---

<br><br>
<div class="box">
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 150%;"><b>Assumption 3.</b> ("Uniform policing intensity by race.")</p>
<p>Police recall by race, $\mathrm{Pr}(s_1 | x, r, d_1)$, is constant in $x$.</p>
</div>

--
<br><br><br><br>
<div class="box">
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 150%;"><b>Assumption 4.</b> ("Uniform camera effectiveness.")</p>
<p>Proxy recall, $\mathrm{Pr}(c_1 | x, d_1)$, is constant in $x$.</p>
</div>

---

# The standard estimator

- When does the odds ratio recover a causal risk ratio?
  - Within $x$, under **Asms. 1–2** (officers & cameras don't lie)
  - Globally, with further **Asms. 3–4** (police/camera uniformity)

--
- Even when local $RR^{d_1,x}$ is recovered, global $RR^{d_1}$ requires careful reweighting .tiny[(Huitfeldt Stensrud & Suzuki '17)]
  - **Asms. 3–4** are a special case where this can be ignored

--
- Do these asms. make sense substantively?

