class: inverse

<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 25%; line-height: 1.5">3.</h1>
<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 20%; top: 25%; line-height: 1.5">
  Benchmarks are a<br>
  special case of negative<br>
  control outcomes
</h1>

---

# Benchmarks as NCOs

- **Negative control:** outcome influenced by unobserved confounders, but not causally affected by treatment

<img src="./resources/images/dag/setup_11.png" style="position: absolute; left: 15%; top: 24%; width: 70%; z-index: ;"/>

--
<br><br><br><br><br>
- Effect restoration with noisily measured confounders
<p style="margin-top: 0ex; margin-bottom: 0ex; line-height: .75">.tiny[(Greenland '05, Greenland & Lash '08, Tchetgen Tchetgen '13, Ogburn & VanderWeele '13, Kuroki & Pearl '14, Wang et al. '18, ...)]</p>

--
- But new challenges from selection on $c_1$ and $s_1$

---

<img src="./resources/images/dag/setup_11.png" style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: -5%; width: 75%; z-index: ;"/>

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

--
$$
\scriptsize
p(c,  r) 
= \textstyle \sum_d\ p(c | d)\ p(d, r)
$$

--
$$
\scriptsize
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 
~p(c_0, r_0) & p(c_0, r_1)~ \\\\
~{\color{#4E84C4}p(c_1, r_0)} & {\color{#4E84C4}p(c_1, r_1)}~
\end{array}\right]
=
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 
~p(c_0 | d_0) & p(c_0 | d_1)~ \\\\
~p(c_1 | d_0) & p(c_1 | d_1)~
\end{array}\right]
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 
~p(d_0, r_0) & p(d_0, r_1)~ \\\\
~{\color{#A51C30}p(d_1, r_0)} & {\color{#A51C30}p(d_1, r_1)}~
\end{array}\right]
\\\\[2ex]
$$

--
- **Without selection:** solve $P\_{dr} = P\_{c|d}^{-1}\ P\_{cr}$ .tiny[(Kuroki & Pearl '14)]

---

<img src="./resources/images/dag/setup_11.png" style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: -5%; width: 75%; z-index: ;"/>

<br><br><br><br><br><br><br>

$$
\scriptsize
p(c,  r) 
= \textstyle \sum_d\ p(c | d)\ p(d, r)
$$

$$
\scriptsize
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 
~p(c_0, r_0) & p(c_0, r_1)~ \\\\
~{\color{#4E84C4}p(c_1, r_0)} & {\color{#4E84C4}p(c_1, r_1)}~
\end{array}\right]
=
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 
~p(c_0 | d_0) & p(c_0 | d_1)~ \\\\
~0 & p(c_1 | d_1)~
\end{array}\right]
\left[\begin{array}{cc} 
~p(d_0, r_0) & p(d_0, r_1)~ \\\\
~{\color{#4E84C4}p(d_1, r_0)} & {\color{#4E84C4}p(d_1, r_1)}~
\end{array}\right]
\\\\[2ex]
$$

- **Without selection:** solve $P\_{dr} = P\_{c|d}^{-1}\ P\_{cr}$ .tiny[(Kuroki & Pearl '14)]
- **With selection, if Asm. 2 holds:**<br>&emsp;&emsp; $p(c_1 | d_0)=0$ &nbsp;&rightarrow;&nbsp; $p(c, r) \propto p(d, r)$



---

# Partial identification of $RR^{d_1}$

1. We want $\Pr(r | {\color{#A51C30}d_1}, x)$, race in dangerous drivers,<br>

--
  but we have $\Pr(r | c_1, x)$, race in camera citations

--
  - Cameras largely correct, with precision $\theta_x = \Pr(d_1 | c_1, x)$

--
  - But proxy is contaminated by $(1 - \theta_x)$ share of safe drivers

--
1. We want $\Pr(r | s_1, {\color{#A51C30}d_1}, x)$, race in justifiable stops,<br>
  but we have $\Pr(r | s_1, x)$, race in all stops

--
  - $RR^{d_1}$ excludes potential discrimination in false charges
  <!-- (problematic, but not part of estimand as defined) -->

--
  - Stops largely justified, with precision $\eta_x = \Pr(d_1 | s_1, x)$
  - But contaminated by $(1-\eta_x)$ share of false charges

--
1. We want $\Pr(x | d_1):$ distr. of dangerous driving, to aggregate local $RR^{d_1,x}$, but we have $\Pr(x | c_1)$

--
  - Partially achieved by **Asm. 4** (uniform camera effectiveness)
  - But distorted by $(1 - \theta_x)$ share of camera false positives

---

<div class="box" style="position: absolute; left: 5%; top: 3%; width: 86%">
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 125%;"><b>Proposition 1. (Simplified*)</b></p>
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 125%;">Under Asm. 4 (uniform camera effectiveness) only, the risk ratio among dangerous drivers is bounded by</p>
$$
\frac{
% lower bound numerator
\sum_x\ N \ \mathbb{E}[ \mathbf{1}(s_1, x) ] \ 
{\color{#A51C30}\big[ \Pr(r_1|s_1,x) + \eta_x - 1 \big]} \ 
{\color{#4E84C4}\frac{\theta_x}{p(r_1|c,x)}}
}{
% lower bound denominator
\sum_x\ N \ \mathbb{E}[ \mathbf{1}(s_1, x) ] \ 
{\color{#A51C30}\Pr(r_0|s_1,x)} \ 
{\color{#4E84C4}\frac{\theta_x}{p(r_0|c,x) + \theta_x - 1}}
}
$$
$$
\large
\le \quad RR^{d_1} \quad \le
$$
$$
\large
\frac{
% upper bound numerator
\sum_x\ N \ \mathbb{E}[ \mathbf{1}(s_1, x) ] \ 
{\color{#A51C30}\Pr(r_1|s_1,x)} \ 
{\color{#4E84C4}\frac{\theta_x}{p(r_1|c,x) + \theta_x - 1}}
}{
% lower bound denominator
\sum_x\ N \ \mathbb{E}[ \mathbf{1}(s_1, x) ] \ 
{\color{#A51C30}\big[ \Pr(r_0|s_1,x) + \eta_x - 1 \big]} \ 
{\color{#4E84C4}\frac{\theta_x}{p(r_0|c,x)}}
},
$$
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 125%;">where $N \ \mathbb{E}[ \mathbf{1}(s_1, x) ]$ is the expected local count of police stops, $\theta_x = p(d_1 | c_1, x)$ is the local precision of camera tickets, and $\eta_x = p(d_1 | s_1, x)$ is the local precision of police stops in spatiotemporal block $x$.</p>
<p style="margin: 0px; font-size: 125%;">
* For $\small 1 - \theta_x < \min_r p(r | c, x)$ and $1 - \eta_x < \min_r p(r | s, x)$
</p>
</div>

---

# Intuition for Prop. 1

- Factually, there are $m = \#{s_1, r, x}$ stops of race $r$ in $x$
  - Suppose no false allegations (all stops of dangerous drivers)
  - Suppose race $r$ is $f = \Pr(r | d_1, x)$ of dangerous drivers in $x$

--
- Counterfactually, we expect $m / f = \#{S(r)=s_1, x}$ if all dangerous drivers were race $r$
  - Recovers $n \cdot \mathbb{E}[S(r) | x, d_1]$

--
- Cannot get risk difference because $n$ is unknown,<br>

--
  but constant of proportionality cancels for risk ratio

--
- However, we don't know:
  - Correct IPW to apply (camera data distorted by miscaptures)
  - Correct # of justifiable stops (distorted by false allegations)

---

class: inverse

<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 25%; line-height: 1.5">4.</h1>
<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 20%; top: 25%; line-height: 1.5">
  A complication:<br>
  race is often unobserved<br>
  and must be inferred
</h1>

---

# Inferring race from names

- Traffic-enforcement datasets often do not record race
- But last name $L$ must be documented in citations<br>
  and can be highly informative about race

<img src="./resources/images/dag/surnames_01.png" style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 40%; width: 75%; z-index: ;"/>

---

# Inferring race from names

- Widely used Bayesian techniques for inferring race
<p style="margin-top: 0ex; margin-bottom: 0ex; line-height: .75">
.tiny[(Fiscella & Fremont '06, Elliott et al. '08, Imai et al. '22)]</p>
- **Essentially:** imputed race is $\Pr(r | \ell)$ from Census

--

