--
<br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br><br>
- Similar approaches used for geography (e.g. $\Pr(r | \text{home ZIP})$)
  .tiny[(Illinois Traffic & Pedestrian Stop Study, '23)]

<!-- .small[**Source:** U.S. Census Bureau. 2016. "Frequently occurring surnames in the 2010 Census."] -->


---

# Standard approach fails under differential selection

- **The problem:** vulnerable to domain shift, <br>
  &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;$\Pr(r | \ell) \ne \Pr(r | \ell, d_1)$

--
- Unconditionally,<br>
    &emsp;$\small\Pr(R=\text{black} | L=\text{Booker}) \approx 2/3$<br>
    &emsp;$\small\Pr(R=\text{white} | L=\text{Booker}) \approx 1/3$
--
- But if white drivers are twice as likely to speed,<br>
    &emsp;$\small\Pr(R=\text{black} | L=\text{Booker}, d_1) \approx 1/2$<br>
    &emsp;$\small\Pr(R=\text{white} | L=\text{Booker}, d_1) \approx 1/2$
--
- Requires correction for $\Pr(r|d)$, which is unknown

---

# Yet another proxy problem

- Inverse problem **is** invariant to domain shift, <br>
  &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;$\Pr(\ell | r) = \Pr(\ell | r, d_1)$

<img src="./resources/images/dag/surnames_01.png" style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 30%; width: 75%; z-index: ;"/>

---

# Yet another proxy problem

- Inverse problem **is** invariant to domain shift, <br>
  &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;&emsp;$\Pr(\ell | r) = \Pr(\ell | r, d_1)$
- Suggests a solution related to McCartan et al. .tiny[('25)]

--
- **Intuition:** relative frequencies of "Booker" and "Yoder" are out of proportion in camera data (vs. Census)

--
  - "Booker" occurs ~33% more
--
, "Yoder" occurs ~100% more

--
  - What is underlying racial distr. that could explain this?<br>

--
&rightarrow; there are 100% more white speeders than black speeders

--
- Special case of 2-sample IV .tiny[(Angrist & Kreuger '92)]

--
- Also closely related to previous NCO methods

---

# Recovering race distribution

- What we have:
  - $\color{#4E84C4}P_{\ell|c_1} = [\ \Pr(\ell | c_1)\ ] :$ surname distr. in camera data
  - $\color{#4E84C4}P_{\ell|r} = [\ \Pr(\ell | r)\ ] :$ surname distr. by race in Census

--
- What we want:
  - $\color{#A51C30}P_{r|c\_1} = [\ \Pr(r | c\_1)\ ] :$ underlying racial distr. in camera data

--
<br><br>

$$\begin{aligned}
\small
\color{#4E84C4}\Pr(\ell|c\_1) 
&= \textstyle \sum\_r \color{#4E84C4}\Pr(\ell|r, \cancel{c\_1}) \color{#A51C30}\Pr(r | c\_1) 
\\\\[1ex]
\color{white}\underset{\scriptsize(\sim10\text{k} \times 1)}{P\_{\ell|c\_1}}
&\color{white}= 
\underset{\scriptsize(\sim10\text{k} \times 4)}{P\_{\ell|r}}\ 
\underset{\scriptsize(4 \times 1)}{P\_{r|c\_1}}
\end{aligned}$$

---

# Recovering race distribution

- What we have:
  - $\color{#4E84C4}P_{\ell|c_1} = [\ \Pr(\ell | c_1)\ ] :$ surname distr. in camera data
  - $\color{#4E84C4}P_{\ell|r} = [\ \Pr(\ell | r)\ ] :$ surname distr. by race in Census
- What we want:
  - $\color{#A51C30}P_{r|c\_1} = [\ \Pr(r | c\_1)\ ] :$ underlying racial distr. in camera data
<br><br>

$$\begin{aligned}
\small
\color{#4E84C4}\Pr(\ell|c\_1) 
&= \textstyle \sum\_r \color{#4E84C4}\Pr(\ell|r, \cancel{c\_1}) \color{#A51C30}\Pr(r | c\_1) 
\\\\[1ex]
\color{#4E84C4}\underset{\scriptsize(\sim10\text{k} \times 1)}{P\_{\ell|c\_1}}
&= 
\color{#4E84C4}\underset{\scriptsize(\sim10\text{k} \times 4)}{P\_{\ell|r}}\ 
\color{#A51C30}\underset{\scriptsize(4 \times 1)}{P\_{r|c\_1}}
\end{aligned}$$

<!-- - **Spoiler:** estimator for $\Pr(r|c_1)$ that respects causal structure &rightarrow; $\widehat{RR}\,^{d_1} > 2$ for both black & Hispanic (vs. white); naive estimator &rightarrow; biased estimates of ${\sim}1.05$ -->

---

class: inverse

<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 10%; top: 33%; line-height: 1.5">4.A.</h1>
<h1 style="position: absolute; left: 25%; top: 33%; line-height: 1.5">
  Application:<br>
  red-light cameras
</h1>

---

# Red-light camera data

- Data from top-10 U.S. police jurisdiction
  - ~100s of cameras
  - ~1M camera-detected violations
  - ~100k corresponding police stops
- $X$ represents spatiotemporal blocks ("QDSBs")
  - Quarter and year (e.g. Jan.–Mar. 2020)
  - Weekday vs. weekend
  - Police work shift (8-hour periods)
  - Police beat (~1 square mile)
- Subset to $X$ with &ge;100 camera-detected violations
  - Retains 88% of camera violations, 68% of police stops

---

# Results

- A generous interpretation of na&iuml;ve approach:

--
  - Reweight stop/camera data to match spatiotemporal distrs.

--
  - Predict $p(r|\ell)$ for each obs. in stop/camera data, aggregate

--
  - Suggests black/white $\widehat{OR}=1.20$, Hispanic/white $\widehat{OR}=1.36$

--
... but results are biased even under **Asms. 1–4**

--
- Proposed approach, accounting for causal structure:
  - Estimate $\Pr(r|x, c_1)$ for each QDSB by proximal inference on surnames
  - IPW-based estimate of counterfactual stop counts, $\propto \mathbb{E}[S(r)=1 \mid d_1]$
  - Under **Asms. 1, 2, 4** (officers/cameras don't lie, uniform camera effectiveness)
  - Black/white $\widehat{RR}^{d_1} = 3.27$, 95% CI $[2.89, 3.76]$
  - Hispanic/white $\widehat{RR}^{d_1} = 3.59$, 95% CI $[3.28, 3.88]$

--
- Caveats and details:
  - Inverse propensity weights trimmed to $[0.1^{-1}, 0.9^{-1}]$
  - CI incorporate uncertainty from estimation of IPW and outcomes 


---

class: inverse

